&gt; It appears that the XML formatter used by the Ant JUnit task (correctly)
&gt; encodes any &#39;&lt;&#39; or &#39;&gt;&#39; characters that appear in the output of the test
&gt; method before including it in the XML output file.
&gt; 
&gt; For example, if in my test method I call
&gt;      fail(&quot;&lt;b&gt;big problem&lt;/b&gt;&quot;);
&gt; 
&gt; then in the XML document, this will appear as:
&gt;      &lt;testcase name=&quot; ... &quot; class=&quot; ... &quot;&gt;
&gt;         &lt;failure message=&quot;&lt;b&gt;big problem&lt;/b&gt;&quot; type=&quot; ... &quot;&gt;
&gt;            ...
&gt;         &lt;/failure&gt;
&gt;      &lt;/testcase&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; Now, when the &lt;junit-report&gt; Ant task processes this file, it copies the
&gt; encoding over to the HTML document, so that when the report is viewed in
&gt; a browser the &lt;b&gt; tag is just interpreted as regular text instead of markup.
&gt; 
&gt; Anyone know how to get markup from a JUnit test across to the output
&gt; from the &lt;junit-reprot&gt; task?
